HUB sk-code PLAYBOOK ROOT
     1	---
     2	title: "sk-code: Manual Testing Playbook"
     3	description: "Operator-facing reference combining the manual testing directory, integrated review/orchestration guidance, execution expectations, and per-feature validation files for the sk-code skill."
     4	version: 3.5.0.16
     5	---
     6	
     7	# sk-code: Manual Testing Playbook
     8	
     9	> **EXECUTION POLICY**: Every scenario MUST be executed against the live sk-code skill — no mocks, no stubs, no "unautomatable" verdicts. Scenarios verify the AI's actual routing behavior: which surface it detects, which references/assets it loads, which agent it dispatches. Acceptable verdicts are PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP (with a documented sandbox blocker).
    10	
    11	This document combines the full manual-validation contract for the `sk-code` skill into a single reference. The root playbook acts as the operator directory, review protocol, and orchestration guide. Per-feature files provide the deeper execution contract for each scenario, including the user request, expected detection markers, expected resource loading paths, and validation criteria.
    12	
    13	---
    14	
    15	This playbook package adopts the Feature Catalog split-document pattern. The root document acts as the directory, review surface, and orchestration guide; per-feature execution detail lives in the category folders at the playbook root.
    16	
    17	Canonical package artifacts:
    18	- `manual-testing-playbook.md`
    19	- `surface-detection/`
    20	- `language-sub-detection/`
    21	- `routing-disambiguation/`
    22	- `skill-advisor-integration/`
    23	- `motion-dev-and-animation-regression/`
    24	- `cross-browser-and-performance-gates/`
    25	- `cross-stack-routing/`
    26	- `design-restraint/`
    27	- `tooling-and-hooks/`
    28	- `plugins-and-hooks/`
    29	
    30	---
    31	
    32	## 1. OVERVIEW
    33	
    34	This playbook provides 31 deterministic scenarios across 10 categories validating the `sk-code` skill surface. Each feature keeps a stable ID (numbered `{PREFIX}-NNN` for legacy categories, or a descriptive kebab-slug for newer non-numbered categories) and links to a dedicated feature file with the full execution contract.
    35	
    36	Coverage note (2026-05-04): the playbook covers sk-code's two-axis routing (Code Surface → Intent → Resource Loading) at SKILL.md head-of-main. It exercises:
    37	- WEBFLOW surface detection (vanilla HTML/CSS/JS frontend with motion.dev / GSAP / Lenis / HLS / Swiper / FilePond markers, `wrangler.toml`, `src/2_javascript/`).
    38	- OPENCODE surface detection (CWD or target path under `.opencode/`).
    39	- UNKNOWN fallback (Go / Swift / React Native markers — disambiguation expected).
    40	- OPENCODE language sub-detection (TypeScript, Python, Shell, JSON/JSONC) with correct sub-language reference loading.
    41	- Routing disambiguation under mixed-marker conditions and the sk-code vs sk-doc anti-pattern.
    42	- Skill advisor integration: confidence ≥ 0.80 win for positive controls, no false positives on doc-edit prompts.
    43	- Motion.dev integration checks: pinned CDN/API smoke, reduced-motion behavior, animation regression baselines.
    44	- Cross-browser and performance gates: Chrome/Safari/Firefox behavior, LCP/CLS/INP thresholds, and compositor-friendly animation checks.
    45	- Cross-stack routing checks: Webflow plus Motion.dev, non-Webflow Motion.dev, OpenCode plus Motion.dev, decision-matrix use, snippet reuse, CWV dual loading, and reduced-motion guidance.
    46	- Design restraint scenarios (added 2026-06-13, v3.4.0.0): the pre-write Design Restraint Ladder rung selection, the implementer anti-stall rule, the `ceiling:` intentional-simplification convention, and the STACK_FOLDERS-to-disk validator.
    47	- Tooling and hooks: the shared `claude-posttooluse.sh` PostToolUse hook's two warn-only banner branches — dist-staleness wiring (`check-dist-staleness.sh`; TH-001, added 2026-07-02, v3.5.0.16) and comment-hygiene wiring (`check-comment-hygiene.sh`; TH-002, added 2026-07-07) — each a deterministic stdout/exit-code check independent of skill routing.
    48	- Plugins and hooks: the runtime-neutral `mk-post-edit-quality` post-edit quality router shared by the OpenCode plugin adapter (`tool.execute.before`/`tool.execute.after`/`experimental.chat.system.transform`) and the Claude Code `PostToolUse(Write|Edit)` hook (`post-edit-quality-router`, added 2026-07-11) — a live dual-runtime dispatch/checker check independent of skill routing.
    49	
    50	### Realistic Test Model
    51	
    52	1. A realistic user request is given to an orchestrator that has the sk-code skill registered.
    53	2. The orchestrator (Claude Code, OpenCode, OpenCode, or Copilot) consults the skill advisor and decides whether to invoke sk-code, route to another skill, or ask for disambiguation.
    54	3. The operator captures: which skill won the advisor vote, which surface sk-code detected, which references/assets the AI loaded, which agent (if any) was dispatched, and what the AI's response actually was.
    55	4. The scenario passes only when the routing is correct, the resource-loading is exact (matches expected paths), and the user-visible outcome is sound.
    56	
    57	### What Each Feature File Should Explain
    58	
    59	- The realistic user request that should trigger the behavior.
    60	- The expected detection markers (verbatim from `references/stack-detection.md`).
    61	- The expected references and assets the AI MUST load (exact relative paths under `references/` and `assets/`).
    62	- The expected agent dispatch (if any — typically `@code` for write work, or none for read-only).
    63	- The pass/fail criteria with binary grading.
    64	- Failure triage steps.
    65	
    66	---
    67	
    68	## 2. GLOBAL PRECONDITIONS
    69	
    70	Motion peer-resource folders must be present before MR/CB scenarios run: `code-webflow/references/animation/` and `code-webflow/assets/animation/`.
    71	
    72	1. Working directory is project root and has `.git/`.
    73	2. The sk-code skill is present at `.opencode/skills/sk-code/` with surface and peer-resource subfolders intact: `references/{router,opencode,webflow,universal,motion_dev}/` and `assets/{opencode,webflow,universal,motion_dev}/`.
    74	3. The skill advisor at `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp-server/scripts/skill_advisor.py` is callable and `skill-graph.json` includes the `sk-code` entry with `signals` array intact.
    75	4. The orchestrator runtime has a Skill Advisor Hook OR can invoke `skill_advisor.py` via Bash.
    76	5. The operator uses sandboxed scratch paths under `/tmp/skc-NNN-sandbox/` for any file fixtures the scenarios need (e.g. fake `wrangler.toml` to trigger WEBFLOW detection).
    77	6. **Concurrency cap**: When running multi-scenario waves, cap at 5 parallel scenarios. Scenarios that invoke `skill_advisor.py` are CPU-light and can run concurrently; scenarios that dispatch `@code` (write work) MUST run serially to avoid scope-collision on the working tree.
    78	7. Destructive scenarios (currently none in this playbook — all scenarios are READ-ONLY against the skill surface) MUST verify recovery is possible if added in future.
    79	
    80	---
    81	
    82	## 3. GLOBAL EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS
    83	
    84	- The exact user prompt that was tested.
    85	- The skill advisor output (top-1 skill, confidence score, gap to second, advisorStatus).
    86	- The detected code surface (WEBFLOW / OPENCODE / UNKNOWN) reported by sk-code.
    87	- The exact list of references/assets the AI loaded (verbatim relative paths under `.opencode/skills/sk-code/`).
    88	- The agent dispatched (if any) with name and runtime (e.g. `@code` via `.opencode/agents/code.md`).
    89	- The AI's user-visible response (the answer it produced or the action it took).
    90	- The scenario verdict (PASS / PARTIAL / FAIL / SKIP) with one-line rationale.
    91	- Output transcripts saved under `/tmp/skc-NNN*.txt` per scenario.
    92	
    93	---
    94	
    95	## 4. DETERMINISTIC COMMAND NOTATION
    96	
    97	- Skill advisor probe: `python3 .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp-server/scripts/skill_advisor.py "<prompt>" --threshold 0.8`.
    98	- Bash commands: `bash: <command>`.
    99	- AI agent prompts: `As @<agent>: <instruction>`.
   100	- Resource path notation: paths shown relative to `.opencode/skills/sk-code/` (e.g. `references/stack-detection.md`).
   101	- `→` separates sequential steps inside a scenario's Exact Command Sequence.
   102	- All evidence files live under `/tmp/skc-NNN*`. The playbook never writes to project paths outside `/tmp/` sandboxes.
   103	
   104	---
   105	
   106	## 5. REVIEW PROTOCOL AND RELEASE READINESS
   107	
   108	### Inputs Required
   109	
   110	1. `manual-testing-playbook.md` (this file).
   111	2. Per-feature files under `manual-testing-playbook/{NN--category-name}/`.
   112	3. Scenario execution evidence (advisor outputs, surface-detection logs, resource-loading transcripts).
   113	4. Feature-to-scenario coverage map (§15 FEATURE CATALOG CROSS-REFERENCE INDEX).
   114	5. Triage notes for all PARTIAL / FAIL outcomes.
   115	
   116	### Scenario Acceptance Rules
   117	
   118	For each executed scenario, check:
   119	1. Preconditions (§2) were satisfied.
   120	2. Exact prompt was used verbatim.
   121	3. Skill advisor returned the expected top-1 skill at the expected confidence band.
   122	4. sk-code detected the expected surface (or correctly returned UNKNOWN).
   123	5. The AI loaded EXACTLY the expected references/assets (no extra loads, no missed loads).
   124	6. The agent dispatch (if any) matched the expected dispatch.
   125	7. The user-visible outcome would satisfy a real user with the originating request.
   126	
   127	### Verdict Rules
   128	
   129	- `PASS`: all 7 acceptance checks true.
   130	- `PARTIAL`: routing correct (advisor + surface + agent) but resource-loading set has minor drift (e.g. extra universal/ load).
   131	- `FAIL`: any of (advisor lost, wrong surface, wrong agent, missing required reference) is true.
   132	- `SKIP`: a documented external blocker (e.g. advisor binary unavailable in sandbox).
   133	
   134	### Feature Verdict Rules
   135	
   136	- `PASS`: all mapped scenarios for the feature are PASS.
   137	- `PARTIAL`: at least one mapped scenario is PARTIAL, none are FAIL.
   138	- `FAIL`: any mapped scenario is FAIL.
   139	
   140	Hard rule: any critical-path scenario FAIL forces feature verdict to FAIL. Critical-path scenarios are SD-001, SD-002, SD-003 (the three primary surface-detection paths) plus CS-001, CS-002, and CS-003 for the cross-stack Motion.dev routing path.
   141	
   142	### Release Readiness Rule
   143	
   144	Release is READY only when:
   145	1. No feature verdict is FAIL.
   146	2. All critical scenarios (SD-001, SD-002, SD-003, RD-002, SA-001) are PASS.
   147	3. Coverage is 100% of playbook scenarios (30 / 30).
   148	4. No unresolved blocking triage item remains.
   149	
   150	### Root-vs-Feature Rule
   151	
   152	Keep global verdict logic and routing-architecture explanations in this root playbook. Put scenario-specific acceptance caveats and resource-path expectations in the matching per-feature files.
   153	
   154	---
   155	
   156	## 6. SUB-AGENT ORCHESTRATION AND WAVE PLANNING
   157	
   158	### Purpose
   159	
   160	This section records wave planning and capacity guidance for the manual testing package.
   161	
   162	### Operational Rules
   163	
   164	1. Probe runtime capacity at start (`pgrep -f "python3 .*skill_advisor" | wc -l`).
   165	2. Reserve one operator (you) as coordinator.
   166	3. Saturate remaining worker slots up to 5 for advisor probes; 1 for `@code` dispatches.
   167	4. Pre-assign explicit scenario IDs to each wave before execution.
   168	5. Run the SA-001 advisor-probe wave LAST so it can reference outputs from SD-* and LS-* scenarios.
   169	6. After each wave, save evidence under `/tmp/skc-wave-NN/`, then begin the next wave.
   170	7. Record utilization, per-feature file references, and evidence paths in the final report.
   171	
   172	### What Belongs in Per-Feature Files
   173	
   174	- Real user request (the human-language ask the operator simulates).
   175	- Exact prompt to feed into the orchestrator's prompt entry.
   176	- Expected detection markers (cite `references/stack-detection.md` line numbers).
   177	- Expected reference/asset load list (exact relative paths).
   178	- Expected agent dispatch (or no-dispatch with rationale).
   179	- Pass/fail criteria.
   180	- Failure triage steps (e.g. "if WEBFLOW not detected, verify markers in code_surface_detection.md:30-37").
