HUB system-deep-loop PLAYBOOK ROOT
     1	---
     2	title: "system-deep-loop: Manual Testing Playbook"
     3	description: "Operator-facing reference for manually validating system-deep-loop hub routing, advisor integration, backend discrimination, state discipline, and per-mode artifact ownership against the live skill registry."
     4	version: "2.0.0.0"
     5	---
     6	
     7	# system-deep-loop: Manual Testing Playbook
     8	
     9	> **EXECUTION POLICY**: Every scenario MUST be executed against the live `system-deep-loop` skill and its real `mode-registry.json` source of truth. No mocks, no stubs, and no invented routing behavior. Acceptable verdicts are PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP with a documented sandbox blocker.
    10	
    11	This document combines the manual-validation contract for the `system-deep-loop` parent-skill hub into a single operator reference. The root playbook acts as the directory, review protocol, and orchestration guide. Per-feature files provide the deeper execution contract for each scenario, including the user request, expected mode, command, agent, backend, artifact root, registry evidence, and binary validation criteria.
    12	
    13	---
    14	
    15	This playbook package adopts the typed per-scenario split-document pattern. The root document acts as the directory, review surface, and orchestration guide; each per-scenario file in the category folders carries typed routing gold in its YAML frontmatter plus the full execution contract in its body.
    16	
    17	Canonical package artifacts:
    18	- `manual-testing-playbook.md`
    19	- `mode-routing/`
    20	- `improvement-lane-routing/`
    21	- `advisor-integration/`
    22	- `runtime-and-backend/`
    23	- `state-and-convergence-discipline/`
    24	
    25	---
    26	
    27	## 1. OVERVIEW
    28	
    29	This playbook provides 20 deterministic scenarios across 5 categories validating the `system-deep-loop` parent-skill hub. Each scenario keeps its stable `{PREFIX}-NNN` ID in a dedicated per-scenario file whose YAML frontmatter carries the typed routing gold and whose body holds the full execution contract.
    30	
    31	Coverage note: the playbook covers the hub's registry-driven routing at version `2.0.0.0`. It exercises:
    32	- Dominant-intent routing for the lexical modes: `research`, `review`, and `ai-council`.
    33	- Explicit mode-hint override routing, such as `research: <request>`.
    34	- The three improvement lanes that share the `deep-improvement` packet: `agent-improvement`, `model-benchmark`, and `skill-benchmark`.
    35	- Advisor integration: the single advisor identity `system-deep-loop`, lexical scoring, alias-fold default behavior, command-bridge behavior, and no false fire on ordinary code-edit prompts.
    36	- The three-tier discriminator: `workflowMode`, `runtimeLoopType`, and `backendKind`.
    37	- State and convergence discipline: externalized state, artifact-root writes, convergence stop behavior, and hub logic boundaries.
    38	
    39	### Realistic Test Model
    40	
    41	1. A realistic user request is given to an orchestrator that has the `system-deep-loop` skill registered.
    42	2. The orchestrator consults the skill advisor, command router, or explicit Skill invocation and decides whether to invoke the hub, a `/deep:*` command surface, another skill, or no deep-loop workflow.
    43	3. The operator captures: which skill won the advisor vote, which `workflowMode` was selected, which command and agent surface would be used, which backend was resolved, which artifact root was named, and what the AI's response actually was.
    44	4. The scenario passes only when the routing matches `mode-registry.json`, the source evidence is quoted or cited, and the user-visible outcome is sound for a real operator.
    45	
    46	### What Each Feature File Should Explain
    47	
    48	- The realistic user request that should trigger the behavior.
    49	- The expected mode, command, agent, backend, and artifact root.
    50	- Why that route is expected, quoting the matching `aliases`, `advisorRouting`, `command`, `agent`, `runtimeLoopType`, `backendKind`, or `artifactRoot` fields from `mode-registry.json`.
    51	- The expected packet and whether it owns mode behavior or the hub only routes to it.
    52	- The pass/fail criteria with binary grading.
    53	- Failure triage steps.
    54	
    55	---
    56	
    57	## 2. GLOBAL PRECONDITIONS
    58	
    59	1. Working directory is the repository root.
    60	2. The hub skill is present at `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/`.
    61	3. `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/SKILL.md` states that `mode-registry.json` is the single source of truth and that the hub holds no per-mode convergence, state, or synthesis logic.
    62	4. `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/mode-registry.json` contains exactly 7 active modes in its `modes` array.
    63	5. The skill advisor at `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp-server/scripts/skill_advisor.py` is callable when advisor scenarios are executed.
    64	6. The orchestrator runtime can invoke `Skill(system-deep-loop)` and can run `/deep:*` command prompts, or the operator can capture equivalent dry-run routing transcripts.
    65	7. Operator evidence is written under `/tmp/dlw-<SCENARIO-ID>/` and never into project source paths unless a scenario explicitly states the mode's real artifact-root contract.
    66	8. Multi-scenario waves cap at 5 parallel advisor probes. Command-bridge and state-discipline checks that may create artifacts run serially.
    67	
    68	---
    69	
    70	## 3. GLOBAL EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS
    71	
    72	- The exact user prompt that was tested.
    73	- The skill advisor output or command invocation transcript.
    74	- The selected `workflowMode`.
    75	- The registry fields used to justify the route.
    76	- The resolved command, agent, packet, backend, and artifact root.
    77	- The AI's user-visible response.
    78	- The scenario verdict: PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP with one-line rationale.
    79	- Output transcripts saved under `/tmp/dlw-<SCENARIO-ID>/`.
    80	
    81	---
    82	
    83	## 4. DETERMINISTIC COMMAND NOTATION
    84	
    85	- Skill advisor probe: `python3 .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp-server/scripts/skill_advisor.py "<prompt>" --threshold 0.8`.
    86	- Skill hub invocation: `Skill(system-deep-loop, "<prompt>")`.
    87	- Command-surface invocation: enter the exact `/deep:*` command and prompt into the orchestrator runtime.
    88	- Registry check: read `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/mode-registry.json` and compare the selected mode to the matching `modes[]` entry.
    89	- Resource path notation: paths shown relative to `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/` unless explicitly stated otherwise.
    90	- All evidence files live under `/tmp/dlw-<SCENARIO-ID>/`.
    91	
    92	---
    93	
    94	## 5. REVIEW PROTOCOL AND RELEASE READINESS
    95	
    96	### Inputs Required
    97	
    98	1. `manual-testing-playbook.md`.
    99	2. Per-feature files under `manual-testing-playbook/{NN--category-name}/`.
   100	3. Scenario execution evidence: advisor outputs, command transcripts, registry excerpts, and AI responses.
   101	4. Feature-to-scenario coverage map in this file.
   102	5. Triage notes for all PARTIAL and FAIL outcomes.
   103	
   104	### Scenario Acceptance Rules
   105	
   106	For each executed scenario, check:
   107	1. Preconditions were satisfied.
   108	2. Exact prompt was used verbatim.
   109	3. The observed route matched the expected registry entry.
   110	4. The command, agent, packet, backend, and artifact root matched the registry.
   111	5. Advisor behavior matched the declared `advisorRouting.routingClass` when the scenario exercises advisor routing.
   112	6. The hub did not invent per-mode behavior outside the packet that owns it.
   113	7. The user-visible outcome would satisfy a real operator with the originating request.
   114	
   115	### Verdict Rules
   116	
   117	- `PASS`: all 7 acceptance checks true.
   118	- `PARTIAL`: selected mode is correct but secondary evidence is incomplete, such as missing artifact-root transcript.
   119	- `FAIL`: wrong skill, wrong mode, wrong command, wrong agent, wrong backend, wrong artifact root, invented registry behavior, or flattened per-mode logic.
   120	- `SKIP`: documented external blocker, such as advisor binary unavailable in the sandbox.
   121	
   122	### Feature Verdict Rules
   123	
   124	- `PASS`: all mapped scenarios for the feature are PASS.
   125	- `PARTIAL`: at least one mapped scenario is PARTIAL, none are FAIL.
   126	- `FAIL`: any mapped scenario is FAIL.
   127	
   128	### Release Readiness Rule
   129	
   130	Release is READY only when:
   131	1. No feature verdict is FAIL.
   132	2. All critical scenarios are PASS: MO-001, MO-002, MO-003, MO-005, IL-001, IL-002, IL-003, AI-001, AI-004, RB-001, RB-003, SC-001, SC-002, SC-004.
   133	3. Coverage is 100% of playbook scenarios: 20 / 20.
   134	4. No unresolved blocking triage item remains.
   135	
   136	### Root-vs-Feature Rule
   137	
   138	Keep global verdict logic and routing-architecture explanations in this root playbook. Put scenario-specific prompts, registry excerpts, acceptance caveats, artifact-root expectations, and triage in the matching per-feature files.
   139	
   140	---
   141	
   142	## 6. CATEGORY INDEX
   143	
