HUB sk-design PLAYBOOK ROOT
     1	---
     2	title: "sk-design: Manual Testing Playbook"
     3	description: "Operator-facing reference combining the manual testing directory, execution expectations, and per-feature validation files for the sk-design parent-skill hub."
     4	version: 1.3.0.0
     5	---
     6	
     7	# sk-design: Manual Testing Playbook
     8	
     9	> **EXECUTION POLICY**: Every scenario MUST be executed against the live sk-design skill - no mocks, no stubs, no "unautomatable" verdicts. Scenarios verify the AI's actual routing behavior: which mode it resolves, which packet it loads, which shared resources it cites, and which advisor decision it follows. Acceptable verdicts are PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP (with a documented sandbox blocker).
    10	
    11	This document combines the manual-validation contract for the `sk-design` parent-skill hub into a single reference. The root playbook acts as the operator directory, review protocol, and orchestration guide. Per-feature files provide the deeper execution contract for each scenario, including the user request, expected router signals, expected resource loading paths, and validation criteria.
    12	
    13	---
    14	
    15	This playbook package adopts the Feature Catalog split-document pattern. The root document acts as the directory, review surface, and orchestration guide; per-feature execution detail lives in the category folders at the playbook root.
    16	
    17	Canonical package artifacts:
    18	- `manual-testing-playbook.md`
    19	- `mode-routing/`
    20	- `advisor-integration/`
    21	- `transform-verb-framing/`
    22	- `md-generator-pipeline/`
    23	- `shared-reference-base/`
    24	- `parity-behavior/`
    25	- `fallback-and-resilience/`
    26	- `hub-manager-intake/`
    27	- `styles-library-utilization/`
    28	
    29	---
    30	
    31	## 1. OVERVIEW
    32	
    33	This playbook provides 42 deterministic scenarios across 9 categories validating the `sk-design` parent-skill hub. Each feature keeps its stable `{PREFIX}-NNN` ID and links to a dedicated feature file with the full execution contract.
    34	
    35	Coverage note: the playbook covers sk-design's parent-hub routing at the current skill files. It exercises:
    36	- Mode routing across the five `packetKind: "workflow"` registry modes: `interface`, `foundations`, `motion`, `audit`, and `md-generator`; plus the one `packetKind: "transport"` mode, `design-mcp-open-design`.
    37	- The mode-hint override rule from the hub: a hint such as `motion: ...` resolves the matching mode.
    38	- Skill advisor integration: `sk-design` wins positive design controls at confidence `>= 0.80`; pure code, documentation, and code-correctness review requests (even with review/audit-adjacent wording) route elsewhere.
    39	- Transform-verb routing from `mode-registry.json`: interface-frame `make it`, audit-frame `should it be`, `aliasOnly`, and excluded aliases.
    40	- The md-generator pipeline as the only mutating mode with `backendKind: playwright-extract` and Write/Edit/Bash access, including its authoring-boundary refusal to fabricate a token table from a brief-only request with no live site.
    41	- Shared reference base usage: the hub stays routing-only, modes cite shared references, and the shared base is not a user workflow.
    42	- Parity behavior proof: selected procedure card rationale, context/proof gates, md-generator preservation confirmation, motion/audit procedure selection, interface variation-set selection, and shared polish-gate selection.
    43	- Fallback and resilience proof: exact no-card fallback lines and direct fallback behavior without subagents, including the md-generator backend-preserving distinction.
    44	- Hub manager-intake proof: context-first intake fields, visible plan before substantial work, verifier-cadence pause when required proof is missing, and design-mode pairing before a design-affecting Open Design run.
    45	- Styles-library proof: eligibility-first retrieval, generation-mismatch refusal, zero-hydration seam validation, corpus-verdict rejection and the generator's leak-gated retry without STUDY.
    46	
    47	### Realistic Test Model
    48	
    49	1. A realistic user request is given to an orchestrator that has the sk-design skill registered.
    50	2. The orchestrator consults the skill advisor and decides whether to invoke `sk-design`, route to another skill, or ask for disambiguation.
    51	3. The hub resolves `workflowMode` from `mode-registry.json` and `hub-router.json` using aliases, router signal classes, transform framing, or an explicit mode hint.
    52	4. The operator captures: which skill won the advisor vote, which mode sk-design resolved, which mode packet was loaded, which shared resources were cited, which tools were used, and what the AI's response actually was.
    53	5. The scenario passes only when the routing is correct, the resource-loading is exact enough to satisfy the feature contract, and the user-visible outcome is sound.
    54	
    55	### What Each Feature File Should Explain
    56	
    57	- The realistic user request that should trigger the behavior.
    58	- The expected mode resolution and why, including aliases and router signal classes quoted from `mode-registry.json` or `hub-router.json`.
    59	- The exact packet and shared resources the AI MUST load, using paths relative to `.opencode/skills/sk-design/`.
    60	- The expected advisor behavior: win, defer, or route elsewhere.
    61	- The pass/fail criteria with binary grading.
    62	- Failure triage steps.
    63	
    64	---
    65	
    66	## 2. GLOBAL PRECONDITIONS
    67	
    68	1. Working directory is the repository root.
    69	2. The sk-design hub is present at `.opencode/skills/sk-design/` with `SKILL.md`, `mode-registry.json`, `hub-router.json`, `shared/`, and all five workflow mode folders plus the `design-mcp-open-design` transport packet intact.
    70	3. The skill advisor is callable either through the runtime hook or through `python3 .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py`.
    71	4. Operators capture evidence under `/tmp/skd-<SCENARIO-ID>/` or `/tmp/skd-<SCENARIO-ID>.txt`.
    72	5. Scenarios outside `md-generator-pipeline/` are read-only routing tests against skill assets.
    73	6. `md-generator` scenarios may write only to sandboxed output paths under `/tmp/skd-*` during execution.
    74	7. Concurrency cap: advisor probes can run concurrently up to 5 workers; md-generator pipeline runs MUST run serially because they use browser tooling and write output artifacts.
    75	8. Styles-library scenarios require Node.js. `SLU-005` also requires the installed design-md-generator backend dependencies.
    76	
    77	---
    78	
    79	## 3. GLOBAL EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS
    80	
    81	- The exact user prompt that was tested.
    82	- The skill advisor output: top-1 skill, confidence score, gap to second, and advisor status.
    83	- The resolved `workflowMode` reported by sk-design.
    84	- The exact packet loaded, relative to `.opencode/skills/sk-design/`.
    85	- The exact list of shared resources and mode resources loaded.
    86	- The tool surface used: read-only for `interface`, `foundations`, `motion`, and `audit`; mutating tool surface only for `md-generator`.
    87	- The selected procedure card when the scenario requests procedure-selection proof.
    88	- The AI's user-visible response.
    89	- The scenario verdict: PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP, with one-line rationale.
    90	
    91	---
    92	
    93	## 4. DETERMINISTIC COMMAND NOTATION
    94	
    95	- Skill advisor probe: `python3 .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py "<prompt>" --threshold 0.8`.
    96	- AI prompt: `As the orchestrator: <instruction>`.
    97	- Resource path notation: paths are relative to `.opencode/skills/sk-design/`, such as `design-interface/SKILL.md` or `shared/register.md`.
    98	- Evidence path notation: `/tmp/skd-<SCENARIO-ID>/`.
    99	- All non-md-generator scenarios write evidence only under `/tmp/`.
   100	
   101	---
   102	
   103	## 5. REVIEW PROTOCOL AND RELEASE READINESS
   104	
   105	### Inputs Required
   106	
   107	1. `manual-testing-playbook.md`.
   108	2. Per-feature files under `manual-testing-playbook/{NN--category-name}/`.
   109	3. Scenario execution evidence: advisor outputs, mode-resolution logs, resource-loading transcripts, and responses.
   110	4. Feature-to-scenario coverage map in this document.
   111	5. Triage notes for all PARTIAL or FAIL outcomes.
   112	
   113	### Scenario Acceptance Rules
   114	
   115	For each executed scenario, check:
   116	1. Preconditions were satisfied.
   117	2. Exact prompt was used verbatim.
   118	3. Skill advisor returned the expected top-1 behavior.
   119	4. sk-design resolved the expected `workflowMode`.
   120	5. The AI loaded the expected packet path.
   121	6. The AI loaded or cited the expected shared resources.
   122	7. The tool surface matched `mode-registry.json`.
   123	8. The user-visible outcome would satisfy a real operator request.
   124	
   125	### Verdict Rules
   126	
   127	- `PASS`: all acceptance checks true.
   128	- `PARTIAL`: routing and packet loading are correct, but resource-loading has minor drift that does not change the workflow.
   129	- `FAIL`: advisor lost unexpectedly, wrong mode resolved, wrong packet loaded, mutation permission used by a read-only mode, or a required shared resource was missed.
   130	- `SKIP`: a documented external blocker, such as advisor unavailability or missing Playwright dependencies.
   131	
   132	### Feature Verdict Rules
   133	
   134	- `PASS`: all mapped scenarios for the feature are PASS.
   135	- `PARTIAL`: at least one mapped scenario is PARTIAL, none are FAIL.
   136	- `FAIL`: any mapped scenario is FAIL.
   137	
   138	Critical-path scenarios are MDR-001, MDR-002, MDR-003, MDR-004, MDR-005, MDR-007, AI-001, AI-002, TV-001, TV-002, MG-001, MG-004, SR-003, PB-001, PB-002, and PB-003.
   139	
   140	Candidate additions for the next operator-confirmed critical-path policy are PB-004, PB-005, PB-006, FR-001, FR-002, HM-001, HM-002, and HM-003. They are not silently promoted by this playbook update.
   141	
   142	Release is READY only when:
   143	1. No feature verdict is FAIL.
   144	2. All critical-path scenarios are PASS.
   145	3. Coverage is 100% of playbook scenarios.
   146	4. No unresolved blocking triage item remains.
   147	
   148	### Root-vs-Feature Rule
   149	
   150	Keep global verdict logic and routing-architecture explanations in this root playbook. Put scenario-specific acceptance caveats and resource-path expectations in the matching per-feature files.
   151	
   152	---
   153	
   154	## 6. SUB-AGENT ORCHESTRATION AND WAVE PLANNING
   155	
   156	### Purpose
   157	
   158	This section records wave planning and capacity guidance for the manual testing package.
   159	
   160	### Operational Rules
   161	
   162	1. Probe runtime capacity at start.
   163	2. Reserve one operator as coordinator.
   164	3. Saturate remaining worker slots up to 5 for advisor probes.
   165	4. Run md-generator scenarios serially.
   166	5. Pre-assign explicit scenario IDs to each wave before execution.
   167	6. After each wave, save evidence under `/tmp/skd-wave-NN/`, then begin the next wave.
   168	
   169	### What Belongs in Per-Feature Files
   170	
   171	- Real user request.
   172	- Exact prompt to feed into the orchestrator.
   173	- Expected router signals quoted from `mode-registry.json` or `hub-router.json`.
   174	- Expected packet and shared resource load list.
   175	- Expected advisor behavior.
   176	- Pass/fail criteria.
   177	- Failure triage steps.
   178	
   179	---
   180	
