.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/manual-testing-playbook.md:13:Source of truth for routing behavior: `.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/SKILL.md` §2 Smart Routing, `.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/hub-router.json` (including `routerPolicy.defaultResourceSemantics: "fallback-only"` and the discovery-only `routerPolicy.discoveryClasses`).
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/manual-testing-playbook.md:21:The scored corpus holds **13 scenario files** under `hub-routing/`: 7 primary routing scenarios (one per mode plus the ambiguous-defer contract) and 6 blind holdouts (one per mode, `blindToRouterKeywords: true`, with any remediation-era vocabulary bindings recorded honestly as `blindExceptions`).
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/manual-testing-playbook.md:36:| MT-004 | [`hub-routing/ambiguous-defer.md`](../manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/ambiguous-defer.md) | `defer` (hub-identity vocabulary only — zero modes score, NO resources assembled, fallback-only contract) |
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/manual-testing-playbook.md:54:MT-H01 is the certified chrome-vs-aside boundary case for the six-mode hub: developer-driven inspection primitives (network requests, live DOM) with no agentic vocabulary must STILL resolve `mcp-chrome-devtools`; `mcp-aside-devtools` wins only when the prompt asks the browser to act autonomously (MT-H04 is the inverse). An `mcp-aside-devtools` or `defer` result on MT-H01 is a routing regression.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/manual-testing-playbook.md:60:- All 13 scenarios resolve to their expected `workflowMode` (or `defer` for MT-004) and assemble exactly the expected packet resources — no more (fallback-only: `defaultResource` is never unioned into a scored route).
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/manual-testing-playbook.md:62:- The genuinely ambiguous scenario (MT-004) defers: zero modes score, no packet resources are assembled, and the Chrome default is at most a defer-time suggestion.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/holdout-agentic-browser.md:24:Prompt: Have the browser sign into the staging portal on its own, click through the checkout flow, and save proof screenshots of every step it takes.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/chrome-devtools-browser-debug.md:22:Prompt: Use Chrome DevTools to capture a HAR for the reducer dashboard failing in staging.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/chrome-devtools-browser-debug.md:30:The router resolves `mcp-chrome-devtools` as a single dominant mode, not an ordered bundle or a deferred disambiguation.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/holdout-browser-inspect.md:20:Prompt: The staging site throws runtime errors on load; I need to inspect its network requests and the live DOM to find the cause.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/holdout-browser-inspect.md:25:With `mcp-aside-devtools` in the hub, this prompt is the chrome-vs-aside boundary case: it must STILL resolve `mcp-chrome-devtools` because it describes developer-driven inspection primitives (network requests, live DOM) with no agentic/AI-browser vocabulary. `mcp-aside-devtools` wins only when the prompt asks the browser to act autonomously (natural-language tasks, sign-in-and-do flows, agent-captured evidence). If the router returns `mcp-aside-devtools` or a defer here, that is a routing regression.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/refero-design-reference.md:22:Prompt: Search Refero for real-app checkout flow screens and pull style references for the redesign.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/refero-design-reference.md:30:The router resolves `mcp-refero` as a single dominant mode. Figma-specific phrasing (render, export tokens, Figma Desktop) must keep resolving `mcp-figma`; a prompt mixing both tools explicitly yields an `orderedBundle` in tie-break order (figma before refero).
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/holdout-design-tokens.md:22:Prompt: Pull the button component's colors and spacing values out of our shared design file and hand them to the build.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/holdout-mobile-pattern-research.md:23:Prompt: Collect how popular phone apps welcome first-time users — real product walkthroughs, not mockups — so we can rework our signup.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/holdout-mobile-pattern-research.md:27:Natural-language MOBILE-app pattern-research intent (no "Mobbin" alias) should resolve `mcp-mobbin`: phone apps + first-run walkthroughs from real products is its app/flow research surface. `mcp-refero` is the adjacent transport but is web/styles-anchored — a defer between the two research transports is a tolerable secondary outcome; `mcp-figma` or a workflow mode is a failure.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/holdout-task-tracking.md:23:Prompt: Close out yesterday's two open items in our project tracker, add a short note on what shipped, and log the hour I spent.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/ambiguous-defer.md:5:title: "Genuinely ambiguous tool request defers rather than silently defaulting"
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/ambiguous-defer.md:6:expected_intent: defer
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/ambiguous-defer.md:8:expected_workflow_mode: defer
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/ambiguous-defer.md:14:# MT-004: Genuinely ambiguous tool request defers rather than silently defaulting
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/ambiguous-defer.md:16:Prompt: Use the MCP tool bridge for this.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/ambiguous-defer.md:20:No specific tool named (no browser, ClickUp, or Figma signal), so the router does not have a strong per-mode signal. `routerPolicy.defaultMode` (`mcp-chrome-devtools`) is a WEAK default per ADR-006 — the router should `defer`/disambiguate on genuinely ambiguous, non-matching intent rather than silently resolving to `mcp-chrome-devtools` on hub-identity vocabulary alone.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/ambiguous-defer.md:22:Hub-identity vocabulary ("mcp tool bridge" here) is discovery evidence only (`routerPolicy.discoveryClasses`): it scores NO mode, so this prompt takes the zero-signal branch. This scenario asserts the **fallback-only** contract for `routerPolicy.defaultResource` (`defaultResourceSemantics: "fallback-only"`): on defer, NO packet resources are assembled — `expected_resources` is empty by design — and the Chrome default is at most the defer-time suggestion offered alongside the disambiguation question, never a silent load.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/ambiguous-defer.md:26:The router does not silently resolve to `mcp-chrome-devtools` on bare hub-identity vocabulary with no per-mode signal: zero modes score, the outcome is `defer`, and no mode resources (including `defaultResource`) are silently assembled.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/mobbin-app-research.md:22:Prompt: Research onboarding flow patterns from real iOS apps on Mobbin and collect screen examples for the signup redesign.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/mobbin-app-research.md:30:The router resolves `mcp-mobbin` as a single dominant mode. Refero-specific phrasing keeps resolving `mcp-refero`; generic "design reference" phrasing naming NEITHER tool may defer for disambiguation between the two research transports rather than silently picking one.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/clickup-task-management.md:22:Prompt: Mark the ClickUp task done and add a note that it shipped.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/figma-transport.md:22:Prompt: Render this component in Figma and export the design tokens.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/aside-browser-automation.md:22:Prompt: Use the Aside browser to sign into the staging dashboard, capture REPL evidence of the console errors, and screenshot the failing widget.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/holdout-web-design-reference.md:23:Prompt: Show me how shipped web products design their checkout pages — concrete screenshots and the styles they use — so I can compare against our redesign.
.opencode/skills/mcp-tooling/manual-testing-playbook/hub-routing/holdout-web-design-reference.md:27:Natural-language design-reference-search intent (no "Refero" alias) anchored on WEB products and styles should resolve `mcp-refero`. `mcp-figma` must not win (nothing references our own design file); `mcp-mobbin` is the adjacent transport but is mobile-app-anchored — a defer between the two research transports is a tolerable secondary outcome, `mcp-figma` or a workflow mode is a failure.

UPSTREAM PLAYBOOK CONTRACT
